{'paragraphs': [{'paragraph_id': 0, 'original_text': 'Educational theory has changed significantly since earlier times, particularly in relation to democracy and accessibility.', 'function': 'Introduces the broad topic of educational theory evolution with focus on democracy', 'craft_move': 'opens_with_declaration_and_scope', 'craft_tags': ['opens_with_declaration', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': 'Strengthen the opening by grounding the abstract claim in a tangible contrast (e.g., past vs. present). Use a declarative sentence to set the stakes, then narrow to democracy and accessibility.'}, {'paragraph_id': 1, 'original_text': 'Before the nineteenth century, the two major figures in educational reform were Locke and Rousseau. Both Locke and Rousseau rejected many widespread educational errors of their time and contributed meaningfully to educational thought.', 'function': 'Introduces key historical figures and their contributions', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_refinement', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_examples', 'layers_parallel_structure'], 'guidance': "Use parallel structure to emphasize their shared role (e.g., 'Locke... Rousseau...'). Refine the claim about their contributions by specifying one or two errors they rejected."}, {'paragraph_id': 2, 'original_text': 'Despite their progressive reputations, neither Locke nor Rousseau extended their ideas to support universal education. Both thinkers focused on the education of a single aristocratic boy, assuming that one adult could devote full time to one child.', 'function': 'Contrasts their reputations with their limited scope', 'craft_move': 'pivots_with_but', 'craft_tags': ['pivots_with_but', 'builds_via_contrast', 'acknowledges_complexity'], 'guidance': "Sharpen the pivot by leading with their progressive reputations, then contrast with the narrow focus. Use 'but' to signal the reversal. Ground the critique in the concrete image of a single aristocratic boy."}, {'paragraph_id': 3, 'original_text': 'This model, while potentially effective, is not scalable because it is impossible for every child to have a full-time tutor. Therefore, the model is limited to a privileged minority and cannot exist in a just society.', 'function': 'Argues the impracticality of their model for democracy', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_escalation', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_escalation', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete', 'closes_with_implication'], 'guidance': "Escalate the argument: start with scalability, then widen to justice. Use a concrete example (e.g., 'a village of 100 children') to underscore the impossibility. End with the implication for justice."}, {'paragraph_id': 4, 'original_text': 'Modern educational thought requires that any acceptable system must be applicable to all children, at least in theory. The ideal educational system must be democratic, even if full realization of this ideal is not immediately possible.', 'function': 'Establishes the democratic principle as a modern ideal', 'craft_move': 'asserts_with_confidence', 'craft_tags': ['opens_with_declaration', 'builds_via_refinement', 'asserts_with_confidence'], 'guidance': "Open with a bold declaration of the modern requirement. Refine the claim by distinguishing between theory and practice. Use confident language (e.g., 'must' rather than 'should')."}, {'paragraph_id': 5, 'original_text': 'This democratic ideal is now widely accepted. The author supports keeping democracy as a guiding principle in educational reform. Any educational method advocated should be capable of universal application.', 'function': 'Reinforces the democratic principle and its implications', 'craft_move': 'layers_parallel_structure', 'craft_tags': ['layers_parallel_structure', 'builds_via_refinement', 'asserts_with_confidence'], 'guidance': "Use parallel structure to link acceptance, authorial support, and universal applicability. Refine the third point by specifying what 'universal application' entails (e.g., 'in principle, if not in practice')."}, {'paragraph_id': 6, 'original_text': 'Individuals may currently use non-universal methods if better than available public options, but such choices should not be considered ideal. The democratic principle, even in a minimal form, is absent in the works of both Locke and Rousseau.', 'function': 'Qualifies the ideal while critiquing historical figures', 'craft_move': 'embeds_qualification', 'craft_tags': ['pivots_with_but', 'embeds_qualification', 'acknowledges_complexity'], 'guidance': "Embed the qualification ('may use non-universal methods') within a larger critique. Use 'but' to pivot to the ideal. Contrast Locke and Rousseau’s absence of the principle with the modern stance."}, {'paragraph_id': 7, 'original_text': 'Rousseau, despite opposing aristocracy, failed to apply his anti-aristocratic views to education. Clarity is essential when discussing democracy and education.', 'function': 'Critiques Rousseau’s inconsistency and emphasizes clarity', 'craft_move': 'pivots_via_contrast', 'craft_tags': ['pivots_via_contrast', 'asserts_with_confidence', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Sharpen the contrast between Rousseau’s anti-aristocratic views and his educational model. Use a concrete example (e.g., 'his Émile') to ground the critique. Follow with a declarative statement on clarity."}, {'paragraph_id': 8, 'original_text': 'Insisting on uniformity in education would be harmful. There are natural differences in ability among children: some are more capable of benefiting from advanced education. Teachers also vary in quality, and it is impossible for all students to be taught by the best teachers.', 'function': 'Argues against rigid uniformity while acknowledging practical constraints', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_contrast', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_contrast', 'acknowledges_complexity', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Contrast the harm of uniformity with the reality of differences in ability and teacher quality. Use concrete examples (e.g., 'a child with dyslexia' or 'a rural school district') to ground the argument."}, {'paragraph_id': 9, 'original_text': 'Even if higher education were suitable for everyone, it is not currently feasible for all to access it. A rigid application of democratic equality might lead to the conclusion that no one should receive higher education, which would be detrimental. Such an outcome would hinder scientific progress and lower the overall educational standard in the future.', 'function': 'Warns against extreme interpretations of democratic equality', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_escalation', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_escalation', 'closes_with_implication', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Escalate the argument: start with feasibility, then widen to consequences (scientific progress, standards). Use a concrete example (e.g., 'medical research') to underscore the stakes."}, {'paragraph_id': 10, 'original_text': 'Progress should not be sacrificed for mechanical equality. Educational democracy must be pursued carefully to preserve existing valuable educational achievements, even if they originated in unjust social conditions.', 'function': 'Balances democracy with the preservation of progress', 'craft_move': 'pivots_via_refinement', 'craft_tags': ['pivots_via_refinement', 'acknowledges_complexity', 'asserts_with_confidence'], 'guidance': "Refine the argument: pivot from the danger of 'mechanical equality' to the need for careful pursuit. Acknowledge the tension (e.g., 'even if unjust') and assert the importance of progress."}, {'paragraph_id': 11, 'original_text': 'An educational method cannot be considered satisfactory if it cannot, in principle, be made universal. Children of wealthy families often receive disproportionate attention from multiple caregivers, such as a mother, nurse, nurserymaid, and domestic servants. This level of individual attention cannot be provided to all children in any feasible social system.', 'function': 'Reinforces the universality principle with a concrete example', 'craft_move': 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete', 'craft_tags': ['pairs_abstract_and_concrete', 'builds_via_contrast', 'closes_with_implication'], 'guidance': "Pair the abstract principle ('universality') with the concrete example of wealthy families. Contrast the disproportionate attention with the impossibility of scaling it. End with the implication for feasibility."}, {'paragraph_id': 12, 'original_text': 'It is uncertain whether such careful, dependent upbringing benefits children, and it may foster parasitic behavior. No impartial observer can justify special educational advantages for the few, except in cases of exceptional need or ability, such as genius or intellectual disability.', 'function': 'Questions the value of privileged upbringing and justifies exceptions', 'craft_move': 'embeds_qualification', 'craft_tags': ['embeds_qualification', 'acknowledges_complexity', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Embed the qualification ('uncertain whether it benefits') within a critique. Use concrete language (e.g., 'parasitic behavior') to ground the argument. Justify exceptions with specific examples (e.g., 'genius')."}, {'paragraph_id': 13, 'original_text': 'At present, wise parents may choose non-universal educational methods for their children, especially for experimental purposes. Such experimental methods should be ones that could, in principle, be extended to all if proven effective. Methods that are inherently limited to a privileged few should not be promoted.', 'function': 'Qualifies the use of non-universal methods while reinforcing the ideal', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_refinement', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_refinement', 'embeds_qualification', 'asserts_with_confidence'], 'guidance': 'Refine the argument: start with the allowance for non-universal methods, then narrow to the condition (extendable if proven). Use confident language to reject inherently limited methods.'}, {'paragraph_id': 14, 'original_text': 'Some of the most valuable developments in modern education originated from democratic contexts. For example, Montessori’s work began in nursery schools in impoverished urban areas.', 'function': 'Provides evidence for the value of democratic education', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_examples', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_examples', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete', 'opens_with_declaration'], 'guidance': "Open with a declarative statement about democratic origins. Use the Montessori example to ground the claim. Emphasize the contrast (e.g., 'impoverished urban areas' vs. 'valuable developments')."}, {'paragraph_id': 15, 'original_text': 'In higher education, exceptional opportunities should be available for those with exceptional ability. Outside of cases involving exceptional talent, there is no justification for educational systems that cannot be universally adopted.', 'function': 'Justifies exceptions for exceptional ability while reinforcing universality', 'craft_move': 'pivots_via_refinement', 'craft_tags': ['pivots_via_refinement', 'asserts_with_confidence', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Refine the argument: pivot from the allowance for exceptional ability to the rejection of non-universal systems. Use confident language (e.g., 'no justification'). Ground the exception in a concrete example (e.g., 'a prodigy in physics')."}, {'paragraph_id': 16, 'original_text': "A second modern trend in education is the shift from ornamental to useful education, which is related to democratic values but more debatable. Veblen’s 'Theory of the Leisure Class' discusses the link between ornamentation and aristocracy, though only the educational implications are relevant here.", 'function': 'Introduces the second trend (ornamental vs. useful) and connects it to democracy', 'craft_move': 'opens_with_declaration_and_scope', 'craft_tags': ['opens_with_declaration', 'builds_via_contrast', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Open with a declarative statement about the trend. Contrast 'ornamental' and 'useful' education. Ground the claim in Veblen’s work, but narrow to educational implications."}, {'paragraph_id': 17, 'original_text': "In male education, this trend appears in the debate between classical education (ornamental) and modern, science-based education (useful). In female education, the conflict manifests as a choice between the ideal of the 'gentlewoman' and training for self-sufficiency.", 'function': 'Illustrates the ornamental vs. useful trend in gendered contexts', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_contrast', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_contrast', 'layers_parallel_structure', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Use parallel structure to contrast male and female education. Ground the abstract terms ('ornamental,' 'useful') in concrete examples (e.g., 'classical education' vs. 'science-based education')."}, {'paragraph_id': 18, 'original_text': "The educational issues concerning women have been complicated by the pursuit of sex equality. Women’s education has often aimed to replicate the education given to boys, even when that education is not inherently valuable. Women educators have sometimes emphasized the same 'useless' knowledge given to boys and have resisted including training related to motherhood.", 'function': 'Critiques the replication of male education for women', 'craft_move': 'builds_via_escalation', 'craft_tags': ['builds_via_escalation', 'acknowledges_complexity', 'pairs_abstract_and_concrete'], 'guidance': "Escalate the critique: start with the complication of sex equality, then widen to the replication of 'useless' knowledge. Use concrete examples (e.g., 'motherhood training') to ground the argument."}, {'paragraph_id': 19, 'original_text': "These conflicting goals make the shift from ornamental to useful education less clear-cut in the context of female education. The decline of the 'fine lady' ideal is a significant example of the broader trend toward useful education.", 'function': 'Analyzes the complexity of the trend in female education', 'craft_move': 'pivots_via_refinement', 'craft_tags': ['pivots_via_refinement', 'acknowledges_complexity', 'closes_with_implication'], 'guidance': "Refine the argument: pivot from the complexity of conflicting goals to the broader trend. Use the 'fine lady' example to ground the claim. End with the implication for the trend’s clarity."}, {'paragraph_id': 20, 'original_text': 'To clarify the argument, the author will focus only on male education for the remainder of the discussion. Several educational controversies are partially shaped by the distinction between useful and ornamental education.', 'function': 'Narrows the scope and introduces key controversies', 'craft_move': 'pivots_from_general_to_specific', 'craft_tags': ['pivots_from_general_to_specific', 'opens_with_declaration', 'builds_via_examples'], 'guidance': 'Pivot from the general (female education) to the specific (male education). Open with a declarative statement about the scope. Preview the controversies to come.'}, {'paragraph_id': 21, 'original_text': 'Examples include: whether boys should study classics or science, with classics seen as ornamental and science as useful. Another issue is whether education should quickly become technical training for a specific trade or profession, where usefulness is a central concern. The debate over whether children should be taught correct speech and polite manners involves questioning whether these are merely aristocratic relics. The value of art appreciation is questioned, particularly for those who are not artists. The proposal for phonetic spelling is another issue influenced by the useful vs. ornamental framework.', 'function': 'Lists controversies shaped by the ornamental vs. useful distinction', 'craft_move': 'deploys_list_with_variation', 'craft_tags': ['deploys_list_with_variation', 'builds_via_examples', 'layers_parallel_structure'], 'guidance': "Vary the structure of each example to avoid monotony. Use parallelism to link the controversies (e.g., 'whether... or...'). Ground each in the ornamental vs. useful framework."}, {'paragraph_id': 22, 'original_text': 'Many educational debates are, at least in part, framed by the underlying conflict between usefulness and ornamentation.', 'function': 'Concludes by summarizing the central conflict', 'craft_move': 'closes_with_restatement', 'craft_tags': ['closes_with_restatement', 'asserts_with_confidence'], 'guidance': 'Restate the central conflict with confidence. Echo the opening of the section (ornamental vs. useful) to create cohesion. Use a declarative sentence to land the point.'}], 'overall_strategy': 'Enhance clarity and flow while preserving the original structure. Strengthen openings with declarative statements or concrete grounding, refine transitions with pivots, and ground abstract claims in examples. Use parallel structure and varied sentence length to improve rhythm. Apply craft moves conservatively to sharpen arguments without altering their core logic. Focus on making the democratic principle and the ornamental vs. useful distinction more vivid and compelling.'}
